  "prompt": "How does the Zika Virus affect men and non pregnant women?",
  "response": "The Zika virus can affect men and non-pregnant women in several ways, although the outcomes tend to be less severe compared to pregnant women and their fetuses. Here are the primary effects on men and non-pregnant women:\n\n1. **Acute Symptoms**: In most cases, Zika virus infection leads to mild symptoms that last for several days to a week. These can include:\n   - Fever\n   - Rash\n   - Joint pain\n   - Conjunctivitis (red eyes)\n   - Muscle pain\n   - Headache\n\n2. **Asymptomatic Cases**: A significant number of people infected with Zika virus do not experience any symptoms at all.\n\n3. **Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome (GBS)**: In rare cases, Zika virus infection has been associated with Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome, a condition where the immune system attacks the peripheral nerves. This can lead to muscle weakness and paralysis, which can be severe and sometimes require hospitalization.\n\n4. **Sexual Transmission**: Zika virus can be transmitted sexually. Men who are infected can pass the virus to their sexual partners. The virus can remain in semen for an extended period, even after symptoms have resolved, so precautions are advised to prevent transmission.\n\n5. **Other Complications**: Though rare, other neurological complications associated with Zika virus infection can occur, such as encephalitis or myelitis.\n\nFor non-pregnant women, the effects are generally similar to those experienced by men. The primary concern for women who are not pregnant but may become pregnant in the future is the potential risk of transmission to a fetus if they contract the virus during pregnancy.\n\nOverall, while Zika virus typically causes mild illness in men and non-pregnant women, its ability to cause severe neurological complications in rare cases and its potential for sexual transmission demands careful attention and preventive measures.",
